{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01B7vx29di2fyo8pPd5FWfDW","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Research Brief (agentic)\n2\t\n3\tUse this when the user asks you to **research a Kaggle competition and write a\n4\tstrategy brief** — typically a natural request like *\"research this competition\n5\tand brief me, with links and a few charts.\"* You (the agent) decide which of the\n6\tskill's individual workflows to run and chain them yourself; this doc supplies\n7\tthe **conventions** for a brief that is accurate, informative, and auditable —\n8\tso the user does NOT need to spell them out.\n9\t\n10\t## How to research\n11\t\n12\tChain the skill's individual research workflows as needed — competition overview\n13\t(`fetch_competition_info`), dataset (`fetch_dataset_info`), discussions\n14\t(`discussion_ingest` then `discussion_query`/`discussion_read`), kernels\n15\t(`kernel_ingest`/`kernel_query`/`kernel_read`, `fetch_top_kernel_scores`),\n16\twriteups (`fetch_leaderboard_writeups`/`fetch_writeup`). Prioritize the\n17\thighest-signal sources; you don't have to read everything.\n18\t\n19\t## Citing sources (hyperlinks)\n20\t\n21\tCite sources as clickable markdown links so the reader can follow up:\n22\t\n23\t- **Public notebooks/kernels:** `[title](https://www.kaggle.com/code/<owner>/<slug>)`\n24\t  using the **real** `owner/slug` you actually gathered — never invent or guess a\n25\t  ref. This exact form keeps each citation checkable against what you gathered.\n26\t- **Discussions / the competition page:** link them too where relevant\n27\t  (`.../competitions/<slug>/discussion/<id>`, `.../competitions/<slug>`).\n28\t\n29\t## Making the brief accurate AND informative\n30\t\n31\tThe brief must be accurate first, then as informative as the gathered evidence\n32\tallows. A strong brief contains all of:\n33\t\n34\t- **Accurate competition mechanics** — the metric, submission constraints\n35\t  (e.g. notebook-only, runtime/internet limits), data shape, and what is being\n36\t  predicted. Get these right; they shape every strategy decision.\n37\t- **Concrete winning techniques, each tied to its evidence.** Don't list generic\n38\t  ML advice. For each technique you surface (e.g. typewell GR alignment, residual\n39\t  modeling, beam search), link the specific notebook or discussion that\n40\t  demonstrates it — so a reader can verify and follow it. A named technique with\n41\t  no source link is weaker than one with a `[kernel](...)` citation; make the\n42\t  citation the rule, not the exception.\n43\t- **A quantified score ladder, assembled into ONE explicit block.** Don't leave\n44\t  scores scattered across prose — collect the concrete numbers you gathered into a\n45\t  single target ladder (e.g. a short list or table): \"carry-forward baseline ≈ X,\n46\t  strong public solutions ≈ Y, top public ≈ Z\", **each rung tied to its source\n47\t  link.** Kernel titles and discussions often embed scores (`[LB 7.776]`, a\n48\t  \"9.251\"-named notebook); harvest those into the ladder rather than leaving\n49\t  performance vague. This turns \"do alignment\" into \"alignment-based solutions sit\n50\t  around Y–Z LB (kernels A/B).\"\n51\t  - **Label a title-embedded number as a title string, not a verified score,\n52\t    unless a fetched LB/CV value confirms it.** A notebook named \"9.251 …\" or\n53\t    \"lb-7-776-…\" asserts that score in its *title* — that is the author's claim,\n54\t    not a leaderboard reading you measured. Present it as \"title claims LB 7.776\n55\t    ([kernel](...))\" unless you actually fetched that kernel's public score; never\n56\t    silently promote a title-embedded number into the ladder as if it were verified.\n57\t- **An actionable implementation path** — a concrete sequence a competitor can\n58\t  start on (baseline → features → modeling → validation → blending), citing the\n59\t  notebook(s) to study at each step.\n60\t\n61\tTwo honesty rules that protect accuracy:\n62\t\n63\t- **Don't let popularity stand in for performance.** Kernel *votes* measure\n64\t  attention, not leaderboard rank — they are NOT a proxy for \"what wins.\" When\n65\t  ranking notebooks, prefer their **embedded/gathered score** where available; if\n66\t  public-score data is unavailable (e.g. the score lookup was rate-limited /\n67\t  429'd), say so explicitly (\"public scores were not retrievable this run\") and\n68\t  state that the ordering is by votes, not rank. Never imply high-vote = high-quality.\n69\t- **Ground every strategic claim to a gathered source, and quantify with sources.**\n70\t  Every technique/recommendation should trace to a notebook or discussion you\n71\t  actually gathered — \"informative\" must never become \"plausible but ungrounded.\"\n72\t  When a source states a concrete number (CV/LB score, ablation delta like\n73\t  \"cabin-side split +0.9%\"), cite it *with its link*. Only cite numbers you\n74\t  actually gathered; never estimate or invent a delta to sound precise.\n75\t\n76\t## Plots (make them auditable by construction)\n77\t\n78\tInclude a few (2–4) plots that give real insight. **Spend the plot budget on\n79\tperformance, not popularity.** Concretely:\n80\t\n81\t- **When you gather leaderboard/score data, convey the score landscape** — where\n82\t  scores cluster, how tight the top is, the gap to beat. The score spread is the\n83\t  single most decision-relevant thing a competitor wants. Convey it **either** as\n84\t  a distribution/bands plot when that genuinely adds insight, **or** as a prose\n85\t  band stating the concrete numbers (e.g. \"top ~5.8, strong public cluster sub-10,\n86\t  starter baselines ~15\"). Use your judgment on which serves the reader better.\n87\t  - **Never a wall of undiscussed names.** What a competitor wants is the score\n88\t    landscape, not a roster. A top-20 chart whose teams are mostly never mentioned\n89\t    in the prose is a wall of orphans — the reader can look up almost none of the\n90\t    bars. So a leaderboard *plot*, if you make one, shows the\n91\t    **distribution/bands** (top score, top-10 band, median, strong-solution\n92\t    cluster) or only the few teams/solutions you actually discuss — never 20\n93\t    named-but-unreferenced rows. Declining a low-value plot in favor of a concrete\n94\t    prose band is good editorial judgment, not a gap; a name-wall is the defect.\n95\t- **Vote / comment-count plots are at most ONE**, and its title must label it as\n96\t  *engagement / popularity, not performance* (e.g. \"Top notebooks by votes\n97\t  — popularity, not leaderboard rank\"). Do NOT fill the plot budget with two or\n98\t  three popularity charts while omitting the score plot — that visualizes\n99\t  attention and hides the thing that actually predicts placement, contradicting\n100\t  the votes≠performance rule above.\n101\t- Remaining plots can be dataset stats, discussion engagement, etc.\n102\t\n103\t**Make every plot legible and useful to a human reader.** A plot that is\n104\tprovenance-clean but unreadable is a failure. Three rules, all required:\n105\t\n106\t- **Human-readable labels — NEVER bare numeric ids.** Label each bar/point with\n107\t  the discussion *title* (trimmed to a readable length, e.g. \"Submission scoring\n108\t  error — is the scorer live?\") or the notebook's short slug/title — never a raw\n109\t  id like `699853` or `697431`, which means nothing to a reader and can't be\n110\t  looked up. If the title is long, truncate with an ellipsis but keep it\n111\t  identifiable. **Keep the id available for traceability** — put it in the\n112\t  sidecar JSON (e.g. an `\"id\"` field alongside `label`/`value`) or as a short\n113\t  parenthetical in the label (`\"… is the scorer live? (#697329)\"`). The human\n114\t  reads the title; the id stays present so the entity remains cross-referenceable\n115\t  to the prose and the value still traces cleanly to gathered data. (The gate\n116\t  traces the `value`, not the label text, so a readable label never regresses the\n117\t  accuracy floor — but keeping the id makes the cross-reference check trivial.)\n118\t- **Every plotted entity must also appear in the brief's prose/tables.** Anything\n119\t  you plot that is an *entity* — a notebook, a discussion, a leaderboard team —\n120\t  must be cross-referenced in the brief's text or a table (ideally with its link),\n121\t  so a reader who sees a bar can find that entity and follow up. No orphan\n122\t  entities: if it's worth plotting, it's worth a row/mention; if it's not worth\n123\t  mentioning, don't plot it. (This is the general case of the leaderboard-plot\n124\t  rule above: a top-N chart of mostly-undiscussed teams is a wall of orphans.)\n125\t  Non-entity bars — histogram buckets, derived distributions, conceptual rungs\n126\t  like \"407–3,263 rows\" — have nothing to cross-reference and this rule does not\n127\t  apply to them. This is checked by a **human reader, not a mechanical gate**:\n128\t  judging \"real orphan vs. legitimate bucket/concept\" is exactly the call a gate\n129\t  can't make soundly.\n130\t- **Every plot earns its place with a one-line takeaway.** Next to each embedded\n131\t  plot, write a single sentence stating what the reader should conclude from it\n132\t  (e.g. \"the top public score sits ~2 RMSE below the strong-solution cluster, so\n133\t  the gap to beat is concrete\"). If you can't state a decision-relevant takeaway,\n134\t  the plot is filler — drop it and use the budget on one that informs.\n135\t\n136\tWorked example — a leaderboard top-N plot (note: plot EXACTLY the rows you\n137\tgathered; if you fetched the top 17, the series has 17 entries and the title\n138\tsays \"top 17\", never padded to 20):\n139\t```json\n140\t{\"title\": \"Public leaderboard — top 17 of N (RMSE, lower is better)\",\n141\t \"source\": \"leaderboard\",\n142\t \"series\": [{\"label\": \"SaintLouis\", \"value\": 5.928},\n143\t            {\"label\": \"Tucker Arrants\", \"value\": 5.955}]}\n144\t```\n145\t\n146\tFor EACH plot, follow this coupled flow so the figure's numbers are provably\n147\treal, not invented:\n148\t\n149\t1. Write the data you will plot to `<name>.json` (next to where the PNG will go),\n150\t   in this schema:\n151\t   ```json\n152\t   {\"title\": \"...\",\n153\t    \"source\": \"<which workflow produced it: kernel_query | fetch_top_kernel_scores | discussion_query | leaderboard>\",\n154\t    \"series\": [{\"label\": \"<human-readable: notebook title/short slug, or discussion title — NOT a bare id>\",\n155\t                \"id\": \"<owner/slug for kernels, discussion id, or team name — the stable key for cross-referencing>\",\n156\t                \"value\": <number>,\n157\t                \"provenance\": \"<verified | title-claim | derived>\"}, ...]}\n158\t   ```\n159\t   Every `value` must be a number you actually gathered from the skill — no\n160\t   invented or interpolated values. If a quantity is incomplete (e.g. some public\n161\t   scores were rate-limited), include only what you have and say so in the title.\n162\t\n163\t   **This schema is universal — EVERY plot, EVERY entry.** Each series entry of\n164\t   EVERY plot (score ladder, votes, discussion engagement, dataset stats — all of\n165\t   them) MUST carry `label`, a single numeric `value`, `provenance`, and `id`\n166\t   where the entry is an entity. Do not use ad-hoc per-plot shapes (e.g. separate\n167\t   `votes`/`comments` keys with no `value`, or a bare `{label,value}` that drops\n168\t   `provenance`) — the renderer and the verifier rely on the common shape, and the\n169\t   tag-aware gate checks `provenance` on every plot. Pick ONE number as `value`\n170\t   (if you want both votes and comments, make two plots or a derived combined\n171\t   metric, each entry still `{label, value, provenance, id?}`).\n172\t\n173\t   **Each entry carries `id` and `provenance`:**\n174\t   - **`id`** — the stable key (kernel `owner/slug`, discussion id, leaderboard\n175\t     team) even when `label` is a human-readable title. The reader sees `label`;\n176\t     `id` keeps the entity cross-referenceable to the brief's prose. It is a\n177\t     reader/author aid, **not a gate key** — orphan-checking (does this entity\n178\t     appear in the prose?) is a human-read judgment, because a gate can't reliably\n179\t     tell a real orphan from a legitimate bucket/derived bar, and opaque ids\n180\t     (e.g. a numeric leaderboard team id) aren't what a reader cross-references by.\n181\t   - **`provenance`** — must be EXACTLY ONE of the closed set\n182\t     `{verified, title-claim, derived}` — these three strings, nothing else. Do\n183\t     NOT invent variants (e.g. `kernel-local-cv`, `discussion-stated`, free-text\n184\t     descriptions): a value outside the closed set is a SCHEMA FAIL, same as\n185\t     omitting the field. If a value is a measured CV/LB number you gathered, it is\n186\t     `verified`; an author's title number is `title-claim`; a computed aggregate\n187\t     is `derived`. It is NOT a free self-assertion:\n188\t     - **`verified`** — the value is present in this run's gathered tool output\n189\t       (the committed verifier can confirm it traces). Only tag `verified` when\n190\t       the value genuinely came from gathered data. **The gate now checks this on\n191\t       EVERY plot regardless of `source`: a `verified`-tagged value that does not\n192\t       trace to gathered data is a hard FAIL** (it cannot hide behind a\n193\t       dataset/derived plot source). So `verified` is a falsifiable claim, never a\n194\t       label of convenience — if you can't point to where this run gathered the\n195\t       value, tag it `title-claim` or `derived`, not `verified`.\n196\t     - **`title-claim`** — the value was parsed from a notebook/discussion *title*\n197\t       (e.g. `9.251` from a \"9.251 …\"-named kernel). Legitimately unverified — it\n198\t       is the author's claim, not a score you measured.\n199\t     - **`derived`** — a computed aggregate (e.g. a histogram bucket, a sum); make\n200\t       the title say so too. Not a raw gathered value.\n201\t\n202\t   **NEVER pad a \"top-N\" plot.** A plot's `series` must contain ONLY rows whose\n203\t   `(label, value)` you gathered in **this run**. If you intended a \"top 20\" but\n204\t   only fetched 17 rows, plot exactly those 17 and title it \"top 17 of N\n205\t   available\" — do NOT round the count up to 20. There are two padding modes, and\n206\t   BOTH are fabrication:\n207\t   - **Invented-from-nothing:** minting a plausible-looking tail entry (a made-up\n208\t     team + score, a discussion id + comment count) that you never saw at all.\n209\t   - **Memory / other-run backfill:** filling a missing row with a *real* entity\n210\t     whose **value you did not gather in this run** — e.g. a discussion id you\n211\t     recognize from training knowledge or a previous run, paired with a comment\n212\t     count this run never fetched. The entity being real does NOT rescue it: the\n213\t     plotted *value* still has no provenance in this run's trace.\n214\t   Build every plot ONLY from what this run actually fetched — never from memory,\n215\t   recognition, or another run's data. Both modes put numbers on the chart the\n216\t   agent never gathered here, and BOTH are caught when the verifier checks each\n217\t   `(label, value)` against THIS run's trace. The number of bars is whatever you\n218\t   truly gathered this run, never a round target.\n219\t2. Write `<name>.py` that **reads `<name>.json`** and renders `<name>.png` from it\n220\t   (matplotlib). The PNG must be a rendering of that JSON — do not plot from any\n221\t   other in-memory data, so the image can never disagree with the saved data.\n222\t\n223\t   **The chart must carry the same claim-vs-verified honesty as the prose.** When\n224\t   a plot mixes `provenance` kinds (the score ladder especially — measured scores\n225\t   next to title-claims), the renderer MUST branch on `provenance` and render the\n226\t   kinds visually distinctly — e.g. hatched or differently-colored bars for\n227\t   `title-claim`, solid for `verified` — plus a legend stating it (e.g. \"hatched =\n228\t   author title-claim, unverified\"). A reader glancing at the chart must not\n229\t   mistake a claimed score for a measured one; a flat chart that draws `7.776`\n230\t   (title-claim) and a measured RMSE as identical bars quietly overstates\n231\t   confidence — the visual equivalent of fabrication. Style by the `provenance`\n232\t   field so the distinction is coupled to the data, not hand-drawn. **Sort bars by\n233\t   value within each `provenance` group** (don't interleave a 9.956 above a 9.251)\n234\t   so the ordering reads cleanly and a reader can scan each band monotonically.\n235\t3. Run the script to produce the PNG, then embed it in the brief with a relative\n236\t   path.\n237\t\n238\t## Why these conventions\n239\t\n240\t- Verbatim `kaggle.com/code/<owner>/<slug>` links let a grounding check confirm\n241\t  every cited kernel is one you actually gathered (catches fabricated refs).\n242\t- The read-from-JSON plot coupling + `{title,source,series}` schema let a\n243\t  provenance check confirm every plotted value traces to gathered data (catches\n244\t  invented/garbled numbers like a vote count rendered 50× too high).\n245\t\n246\tThese hold the quality bar without the user having to ask for them.\n247\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dc87655d-e6ca-4a83-a259-05b02b16b06f","uuid":"ea76bda2-ab17-4870-ad78-f413ab65bf8d","timestamp":"2026-06-13T15:01:56.210Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/nvidia-kaggle/.claude/skills/nvidia-kaggle-skill/research-brief.md","content":"# Research Brief (agentic)\n\nUse this when the user asks you to **research a Kaggle competition and write a\nstrategy brief** — typically a natural request like *\"research this competition\nand brief me, with links and a few charts.\"* You (the agent) decide which of the\nskill's individual workflows to run and chain them yourself; this doc supplies\nthe **conventions** for a brief that is accurate, informative, and auditable —\nso the user does NOT need to spell them out.\n\n## How to research\n\nChain the skill's individual research workflows as needed — competition overview\n(`fetch_competition_info`), dataset (`fetch_dataset_info`), discussions\n(`discussion_ingest` then `discussion_query`/`discussion_read`), kernels\n(`kernel_ingest`/`kernel_query`/`kernel_read`, `fetch_top_kernel_scores`),\nwriteups (`fetch_leaderboard_writeups`/`fetch_writeup`). Prioritize the\nhighest-signal sources; you don't have to read everything.\n\n## Citing sources (hyperlinks)\n\nCite sources as clickable markdown links so the reader can follow up:\n\n- **Public notebooks/kernels:** `[title](https://www.kaggle.com/code/<owner>/<slug>)`\n  using the **real** `owner/slug` you actually gathered — never invent or guess a\n  ref. This exact form keeps each citation checkable against what you gathered.\n- **Discussions / the competition page:** link them too where relevant\n  (`.../competitions/<slug>/discussion/<id>`, `.../competitions/<slug>`).\n\n## Making the brief accurate AND informative\n\nThe brief must be accurate first, then as informative as the gathered evidence\nallows. A strong brief contains all of:\n\n- **Accurate competition mechanics** — the metric, submission constraints\n  (e.g. notebook-only, runtime/internet limits), data shape, and what is being\n  predicted. Get these right; they shape every strategy decision.\n- **Concrete winning techniques, each tied to its evidence.** Don't list generic\n  ML advice. For each technique you surface (e.g. typewell GR alignment, residual\n  modeling, beam search), link the specific notebook or discussion that\n  demonstrates it — so a reader can verify and follow it. A named technique with\n  no source link is weaker than one with a `[kernel](...)` citation; make the\n  citation the rule, not the exception.\n- **A quantified score ladder, assembled into ONE explicit block.** Don't leave\n  scores scattered across prose — collect the concrete numbers you gathered into a\n  single target ladder (e.g. a short list or table): \"carry-forward baseline ≈ X,\n  strong public solutions ≈ Y, top public ≈ Z\", **each rung tied to its source\n  link.** Kernel titles and discussions often embed scores (`[LB 7.776]`, a\n  \"9.251\"-named notebook); harvest those into the ladder rather than leaving\n  performance vague. This turns \"do alignment\" into \"alignment-based solutions sit\n  around Y–Z LB (kernels A/B).\"\n  - **Label a title-embedded number as a title string, not a verified score,\n    unless a fetched LB/CV value confirms it.** A notebook named \"9.251 …\" or\n    \"lb-7-776-…\" asserts that score in its *title* — that is the author's claim,\n    not a leaderboard reading you measured. Present it as \"title claims LB 7.776\n    ([kernel](...))\" unless you actually fetched that kernel's public score; never\n    silently promote a title-embedded number into the ladder as if it were verified.\n- **An actionable implementation path** — a concrete sequence a competitor can\n  start on (baseline → features → modeling → validation → blending), citing the\n  notebook(s) to study at each step.\n\nTwo honesty rules that protect accuracy:\n\n- **Don't let popularity stand in for performance.** Kernel *votes* measure\n  attention, not leaderboard rank — they are NOT a proxy for \"what wins.\" When\n  ranking notebooks, prefer their **embedded/gathered score** where available; if\n  public-score data is unavailable (e.g. the score lookup was rate-limited /\n  429'd), say so explicitly (\"public scores were not retrievable this run\") and\n  state that the ordering is by votes, not rank. Never imply high-vote = high-quality.\n- **Ground every strategic claim to a gathered source, and quantify with sources.**\n  Every technique/recommendation should trace to a notebook or discussion you\n  actually gathered — \"informative\" must never become \"plausible but ungrounded.\"\n  When a source states a concrete number (CV/LB score, ablation delta like\n  \"cabin-side split +0.9%\"), cite it *with its link*. Only cite numbers you\n  actually gathered; never estimate or invent a delta to sound precise.\n\n## Plots (make them auditable by construction)\n\nInclude a few (2–4) plots that give real insight. **Spend the plot budget on\nperformance, not popularity.** Concretely:\n\n- **When you gather leaderboard/score data, convey the score landscape** — where\n  scores cluster, how tight the top is, the gap to beat. The score spread is the\n  single most decision-relevant thing a competitor wants. Convey it **either** as\n  a distribution/bands plot when that genuinely adds insight, **or** as a prose\n  band stating the concrete numbers (e.g. \"top ~5.8, strong public cluster sub-10,\n  starter baselines ~15\"). Use your judgment on which serves the reader better.\n  - **Never a wall of undiscussed names.** What a competitor wants is the score\n    landscape, not a roster. A top-20 chart whose teams are mostly never mentioned\n    in the prose is a wall of orphans — the reader can look up almost none of the\n    bars. So a leaderboard *plot*, if you make one, shows the\n    **distribution/bands** (top score, top-10 band, median, strong-solution\n    cluster) or only the few teams/solutions you actually discuss — never 20\n    named-but-unreferenced rows. Declining a low-value plot in favor of a concrete\n    prose band is good editorial judgment, not a gap; a name-wall is the defect.\n- **Vote / comment-count plots are at most ONE**, and its title must label it as\n  *engagement / popularity, not performance* (e.g. \"Top notebooks by votes\n  — popularity, not leaderboard rank\"). Do NOT fill the plot budget with two or\n  three popularity charts while omitting the score plot — that visualizes\n  attention and hides the thing that actually predicts placement, contradicting\n  the votes≠performance rule above.\n- Remaining plots can be dataset stats, discussion engagement, etc.\n\n**Make every plot legible and useful to a human reader.** A plot that is\nprovenance-clean but unreadable is a failure. Three rules, all required:\n\n- **Human-readable labels — NEVER bare numeric ids.** Label each bar/point with\n  the discussion *title* (trimmed to a readable length, e.g. \"Submission scoring\n  error — is the scorer live?\") or the notebook's short slug/title — never a raw\n  id like `699853` or `697431`, which means nothing to a reader and can't be\n  looked up. If the title is long, truncate with an ellipsis but keep it\n  identifiable. **Keep the id available for traceability** — put it in the\n  sidecar JSON (e.g. an `\"id\"` field alongside `label`/`value`) or as a short\n  parenthetical in the label (`\"… is the scorer live? (#697329)\"`). The human\n  reads the title; the id stays present so the entity remains cross-referenceable\n  to the prose and the value still traces cleanly to gathered data. (The gate\n  traces the `value`, not the label text, so a readable label never regresses the\n  accuracy floor — but keeping the id makes the cross-reference check trivial.)\n- **Every plotted entity must also appear in the brief's prose/tables.** Anything\n  you plot that is an *entity* — a notebook, a discussion, a leaderboard team —\n  must be cross-referenced in the brief's text or a table (ideally with its link),\n  so a reader who sees a bar can find that entity and follow up. No orphan\n  entities: if it's worth plotting, it's worth a row/mention; if it's not worth\n  mentioning, don't plot it. (This is the general case of the leaderboard-plot\n  rule above: a top-N chart of mostly-undiscussed teams is a wall of orphans.)\n  Non-entity bars — histogram buckets, derived distributions, conceptual rungs\n  like \"407–3,263 rows\" — have nothing to cross-reference and this rule does not\n  apply to them. This is checked by a **human reader, not a mechanical gate**:\n  judging \"real orphan vs. legitimate bucket/concept\" is exactly the call a gate\n  can't make soundly.\n- **Every plot earns its place with a one-line takeaway.** Next to each embedded\n  plot, write a single sentence stating what the reader should conclude from it\n  (e.g. \"the top public score sits ~2 RMSE below the strong-solution cluster, so\n  the gap to beat is concrete\"). If you can't state a decision-relevant takeaway,\n  the plot is filler — drop it and use the budget on one that informs.\n\nWorked example — a leaderboard top-N plot (note: plot EXACTLY the rows you\ngathered; if you fetched the top 17, the series has 17 entries and the title\nsays \"top 17\", never padded to 20):\n```json\n{\"title\": \"Public leaderboard — top 17 of N (RMSE, lower is better)\",\n \"source\": \"leaderboard\",\n \"series\": [{\"label\": \"SaintLouis\", \"value\": 5.928},\n            {\"label\": \"Tucker Arrants\", \"value\": 5.955}]}\n```\n\nFor EACH plot, follow this coupled flow so the figure's numbers are provably\nreal, not invented:\n\n1. Write the data you will plot to `<name>.json` (next to where the PNG will go),\n   in this schema:\n   ```json\n   {\"title\": \"...\",\n    \"source\": \"<which workflow produced it: kernel_query | fetch_top_kernel_scores | discussion_query | leaderboard>\",\n    \"series\": [{\"label\": \"<human-readable: notebook title/short slug, or discussion title — NOT a bare id>\",\n                \"id\": \"<owner/slug for kernels, discussion id, or team name — the stable key for cross-referencing>\",\n                \"value\": <number>,\n                \"provenance\": \"<verified | title-claim | derived>\"}, ...]}\n   ```\n   Every `value` must be a number you actually gathered from the skill — no\n   invented or interpolated values. If a quantity is incomplete (e.g. some public\n   scores were rate-limited), include only what you have and say so in the title.\n\n   **This schema is universal — EVERY plot, EVERY entry.** Each series entry of\n   EVERY plot (score ladder, votes, discussion engagement, dataset stats — all of\n   them) MUST carry `label`, a single numeric `value`, `provenance`, and `id`\n   where the entry is an entity. Do not use ad-hoc per-plot shapes (e.g. separate\n   `votes`/`comments` keys with no `value`, or a bare `{label,value}` that drops\n   `provenance`) — the renderer and the verifier rely on the common shape, and the\n   tag-aware gate checks `provenance` on every plot. Pick ONE number as `value`\n   (if you want both votes and comments, make two plots or a derived combined\n   metric, each entry still `{label, value, provenance, id?}`).\n\n   **Each entry carries `id` and `provenance`:**\n   - **`id`** — the stable key (kernel `owner/slug`, discussion id, leaderboard\n     team) even when `label` is a human-readable title. The reader sees `label`;\n     `id` keeps the entity cross-referenceable to the brief's prose. It is a\n     reader/author aid, **not a gate key** — orphan-checking (does this entity\n     appear in the prose?) is a human-read judgment, because a gate can't reliably\n     tell a real orphan from a legitimate bucket/derived bar, and opaque ids\n     (e.g. a numeric leaderboard team id) aren't what a reader cross-references by.\n   - **`provenance`** — must be EXACTLY ONE of the closed set\n     `{verified, title-claim, derived}` — these three strings, nothing else. Do\n     NOT invent variants (e.g. `kernel-local-cv`, `discussion-stated`, free-text\n     descriptions): a value outside the closed set is a SCHEMA FAIL, same as\n     omitting the field. If a value is a measured CV/LB number you gathered, it is\n     `verified`; an author's title number is `title-claim`; a computed aggregate\n     is `derived`. It is NOT a free self-assertion:\n     - **`verified`** — the value is present in this run's gathered tool output\n       (the committed verifier can confirm it traces). Only tag `verified` when\n       the value genuinely came from gathered data. **The gate now checks this on\n       EVERY plot regardless of `source`: a `verified`-tagged value that does not\n       trace to gathered data is a hard FAIL** (it cannot hide behind a\n       dataset/derived plot source). So `verified` is a falsifiable claim, never a\n       label of convenience — if you can't point to where this run gathered the\n       value, tag it `title-claim` or `derived`, not `verified`.\n     - **`title-claim`** — the value was parsed from a notebook/discussion *title*\n       (e.g. `9.251` from a \"9.251 …\"-named kernel). Legitimately unverified — it\n       is the author's claim, not a score you measured.\n     - **`derived`** — a computed aggregate (e.g. a histogram bucket, a sum); make\n       the title say so too. Not a raw gathered value.\n\n   **NEVER pad a \"top-N\" plot.** A plot's `series` must contain ONLY rows whose\n   `(label, value)` you gathered in **this run**. If you intended a \"top 20\" but\n   only fetched 17 rows, plot exactly those 17 and title it \"top 17 of N\n   available\" — do NOT round the count up to 20. There are two padding modes, and\n   BOTH are fabrication:\n   - **Invented-from-nothing:** minting a plausible-looking tail entry (a made-up\n     team + score, a discussion id + comment count) that you never saw at all.\n   - **Memory / other-run backfill:** filling a missing row with a *real* entity\n     whose **value you did not gather in this run** — e.g. a discussion id you\n     recognize from training knowledge or a previous run, paired with a comment\n     count this run never fetched. The entity being real does NOT rescue it: the\n     plotted *value* still has no provenance in this run's trace.\n   Build every plot ONLY from what this run actually fetched — never from memory,\n   recognition, or another run's data. Both modes put numbers on the chart the\n   agent never gathered here, and BOTH are caught when the verifier checks each\n   `(label, value)` against THIS run's trace. The number of bars is whatever you\n   truly gathered this run, never a round target.\n2. Write `<name>.py` that **reads `<name>.json`** and renders `<name>.png` from it\n   (matplotlib). The PNG must be a rendering of that JSON — do not plot from any\n   other in-memory data, so the image can never disagree with the saved data.\n\n   **The chart must carry the same claim-vs-verified honesty as the prose.** When\n   a plot mixes `provenance` kinds (the score ladder especially — measured scores\n   next to title-claims), the renderer MUST branch on `provenance` and render the\n   kinds visually distinctly — e.g. hatched or differently-colored bars for\n   `title-claim`, solid for `verified` — plus a legend stating it (e.g. \"hatched =\n   author title-claim, unverified\"). A reader glancing at the chart must not\n   mistake a claimed score for a measured one; a flat chart that draws `7.776`\n   (title-claim) and a measured RMSE as identical bars quietly overstates\n   confidence — the visual equivalent of fabrication. Style by the `provenance`\n   field so the distinction is coupled to the data, not hand-drawn. **Sort bars by\n   value within each `provenance` group** (don't interleave a 9.956 above a 9.251)\n   so the ordering reads cleanly and a reader can scan each band monotonically.\n3. Run the script to produce the PNG, then embed it in the brief with a relative\n   path.\n\n## Why these conventions\n\n- Verbatim `kaggle.com/code/<owner>/<slug>` links let a grounding check confirm\n  every cited kernel is one you actually gathered (catches fabricated refs).\n- The read-from-JSON plot coupling + `{title,source,series}` schema let a\n  provenance check confirm every plotted value traces to gathered data (catches\n  invented/garbled numbers like a vote count rendered 50× too high).\n\nThese hold the quality bar without the user having to ask for them.\n","numLines":247,"startLine":1,"totalLines":247}}}
